Church fire in Nantes, France: Parish volunteer admits arson is usually kind-hearted-<url>
Beijing, July 26, according to foreign media reports, on July 18, Nantes, France, the religious historical architectural treasures,the famous Cathedral of St. Peter and St. Paul, in a fire was seriously damaged, the organ completely destroyed.
On the 26th local time, Nantes prosecutors announced that a parish volunteer in charge of the protection of the cathedral has been charged with“arson destruction.”
He had admitted that he had set the fire in the church.
Local prosecutor Senas said the 39-year-old parish volunteer from Rwanda admitted he set three fires in the cathedral during the night, according to the report.
The man's lawyer said the arsonist now regretted doing so.
The man entered France a few years ago by way of refuge, was sheltered in the parish where the fire occurred, and was taken into custody in the church.
Prosecutors said he had recently tried to renew his visa and was in conversation with the police.
But the church said it still could not believe that the usually very kind, smiling, but not very talkative believer would destroy the church he loved so much.
On the day of the fire on July 18, the volunteer had been questioned by the police because of illogical problems in the narrative, but he was later released.
The picture shows firefighters at the scene to rescue.
On the evening of the 25th, the man was arraigned again as a professional engineer in the laboratory of the Paris Central Police Department obtained new evidence.
This time, the man admitted to his act of arson.
If convicted of arson, the suspect could face up to 10 years in prison and a fine of 150,000 euros, according to reports.
The report said that the fire caused serious damage to the cathedral of St. Pierre and St. Paul, the church organ was completely burned down, the stained glass windows behind the organ was also badly damaged.
Brunet, the chief architect of historic preservation in France, believes that the restoration of Nantes Cathedral will take at least three years, according to a conservative estimate.
Comprehensive News: US Unilateralism undermines Bilateral Relations International Public Opinion supports China's counter-system against the United States-Xinhua
Beijing, July 26 (Xinhua) -- On the morning of July 24, the Chinese Ministry of Foreign Affairs informed the U.S. Embassy in China that China had decided to revoke the permission for the establishment and operation of the U.S. Consulate General in Chengdu and made specific requests for the Consulate General to cease all operations and activities.
International public opinion believes that the unilateral measures taken by the United States have caused serious distress to the relations between China and the United States, and that it is legitimate and necessary for China to respond to the unjustified provocations of the United States and take counter-measures.
Andres Borkes, director of the Center for China Studies at the Institute of International Studies at the University of Chile, said the unilateralist measures in the United States have undermined the bridge of understanding between the two peoples and put the relationship between the two great powers at risk.
China has informed the United States that the closure of its Consulate general in Chengdu is a response to unilateral measures by the United States and is in line with diplomatic practice.
Patricio Giusto, a professor at the Catholic University of Argentina and director of the Arab-Chinese Research Center, believes that China's decision is a legitimate and necessary counter-measure against the previous provocations of the United States, not against the ordinary American people.
The United States is trying to distract the American public by pressuring China to cover up its weak response to the new crown outbreak.
Banbang Surjono, chairman of the Asian Innovation Research Center, an Indonesian think tank, said the provocative diplomatic gesture by the United States has caused serious distress to relations between the Two countries and faced serious challenges.
China has informed the United States that the closure of its Consulate General in Chengdu is a normal counter-measure and is in line with diplomatic practice. It reflects not only China's principled position of resolutely safeguarding its own interests, but also the rational and beneficial interests of Chinese diplomacy.
Francis Semwenza, a Tanzanian current affairs commentator, said China's decision was a legitimate and necessary response to U.S. provocations.
The U.S. side should take the initiative to improve relations with China and stop interfering in China's internal affairs.
The United States should focus on how to achieve economic and political win-win with China, and how to benefit the people of both countries and the international community as a whole.
Ali Youssef, executive Director of the Sudan－based Federation of Arab-Chinese Friendship Associations, said China's forced countermeasures were a legitimate and necessary response to the unjustified actions of the United States, in line with international law and basic norms of international relations, as well as diplomatic practice.
The U.S. request to close the Chinese Consulate General in Houston is a serious violation of international law and the basic norms of international relations.
It is hoped that the United States will rescind the previous decision and create the necessary conditions for the return of relations between the two countries to normalcy.
Singapore's Lianhe Zaobao said in an editorial that America's greater strategic intention is to contain China and prevent it from continuing to rise.
In the face of US pressure, China is reluctant to see China-US relations continue to deteriorate, but has to take counter-measures.
(Participating journalists: Yin Nan, Zhang Xiaoran,Ni Ruijie,Liang Hui,Gao Zhu,Li Sibo,Ma Yichong, Wang Lili）
