Engine may Stall FAA Orders 2,000 Boeing airliners-Xinhua
The United States Federal Aviation Administration (FAA)issued an emergency airworthiness directive on the 24th, requiring emergency inspection of about 2,000 Boeing 737NG and 737Classic aircraft registered in the United States, because the air check valve corrosion of the aircraft may cause the engine to stop in the air.
The FAA said it had so far received four reports of aerial parking of the engines of the 737NG and 737Classic aircraft, resulting in an emergency inspection request for aircraft that had been parked for seven consecutive days or more and for aircraft that had flown less than 11 times since re-entering the aircraft.
The FAA has warned that the Class 5 check valves on all two of the aircraft's engines, if corroded, could become stuck in the open position, causing the aircraft to lose power completely and be unable to restart the engine.
The aviation regulator ordered that if the check valve was found to be corroded, the airline operator must replace the critical component before the aircraft is put into service again.
Boeing responded later in the day that the outbreak of the new crown outbreak led to reduced travel demand, and many airliners were mothballed or used less, “ check valves are more vulnerable to corrosion. ”
Boeing also said it had advised air carriers to inspect the airliners involved in the directive, and if problems were found, Boeing would provide assistance in overhauling and replacing check valves.
airliners owned by major U.S. air carriers usually fly multiple times a day, but a large number of airliners have been grounded after the new crown outbreak, and some have been put back into operation as demand for passenger travel has recently grown slowly, the Associated Press reported.
The FAA did not release the details of the four aerial parking reports.
Alaska Airlines disclosed one of the incidents late on the 24th.
The airline said in a statement that one of its airliners made an emergency landing at Austin Airport on July 15 when an engine suddenly stalled on the way from Seattle, Washington, to Austin, Texas.
Alaska Airlines says it has replaced the engine of the airliner and has inspected the engines of six airliners in accordance with FAA instructions.
American Airlines, United Airlines and Southwest Airlines said on the 24th, respectively, its passenger aircraft did not appear associated with the air check valve engine flameout.
Four of American Airlines ' aircraft will be inspected and 28 of United's aircraft will be inspected.
Delta said it would inspect 20 of its airliners, but did not say whether there had been engine failures.
A number of media reports, the FAA emergency airworthiness directive is another shock to Boeing.
Indonesian Lion Airlines and Ethiopian Airlines each crashed a Boeing 737MAX airliner in October 2018 and March 2019, respectively, killing a total of 346 people.
The series of airliners was subsequently grounded worldwide,discontinued in January and resumed production in May.
FAA Chief Steve Dickson admitted in June that the FAA had“made a mistake” in regulating Boeing on the 737MAX.
