Recently, a Brazilian study showed that hydroxychloroquine is not effective in patients with mild and moderate new crown pneumonia.
The study was published in the New England Journal of Medicine.
The Pakistani researchers divided 667 patients in 55 hospitals across the country into three groups and conducted clinical trials, comparing the effects of hydroxychloroquine alone or in combination with other antibiotics, azithromycin, to determine whether it could help improve the condition of mild and moderate patients with new crown pneumonia.
The results show that hydroxychloroquine not only has no therapeutic effect, but may have damaging side effects on the organs.
The study was conducted in conjunction with the Brazilian Clinical Research Institute(BCRI) and the Brazilian Intensive Care Research Network(BRICNet) by leading Brazilian hospitals such as Hospital Israelita Albert Einstein, Hospital of Cardiology(HCor)and Hospital Sírio-Libanês in Syria and Lebanon.
