APEC Member Trade Ministers ' Meeting says it will accelerate regional economic recovery-Xinhua
Xinhua News Agency, Kuala Lumpur, July 25 (Reporter Lin Hao) Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC) member trade ministers held a video conference on the 25th, the meeting promised to work to reduce the impact of the new crown epidemic on the region's economy and accelerate the achievement of a resilient, sustainable and inclusive regional economic recovery.
The meeting was hosted by Malaysia, the host of this year's informal meeting of APEC leaders.
A joint statement issued after the meeting said that APEC member trade ministers recognized the importance of a free, open, fair, non-discriminatory, transparent and predictable trade and investment environment to drive economic recovery at this challenging time.
All parties are committed to ensuring that emergency measures taken to respond to the outbreak are targeted, appropriate, transparent and temporary, do not create unnecessary trade barriers and disrupt global supply chains, while complying with World Trade Organization rules.
In a statement, APEC member trade ministers pledged to strengthen cooperation to facilitate the flow of necessary goods and services, promote connectivity through enhanced supply chain resiliency, and minimize disruption to the flow of medical supplies, food and agricultural products in response to the outbreak.
Trade ministers of APEC members agreed on the need to discuss ways to reduce non-tariff barriers that limit trade in essential commodities and reiterated their commitment to promote the necessary cross-border movement of people without prejudice to measures taken to stop the spread of the epidemic.
The conference also issued a declaration on the promotion of the circulation of essential commodities.
The declaration said that economies would ensure that their trade measures in response to the outbreak were in line with WTO rules and pledged to take action to reduce non-tariff trade barriers and trade promotion to facilitate the flow of goods necessary for the outbreak.
Malaysia's Minister of International Trade and Industry, Azmin Ali, who chaired the meeting, said that despite the impact of the outbreak, Malaysia remained committed to the success of this year's APEC conference and that work on developing a vision for APEC post-2020 cooperation is proceeding in an orderly manner.
Malaysia agreed to hold APEC-related meetings in video format, but did not rule out the possibility of scheduling a physical meeting during an informal meeting of APEC leaders at the end of the year.
