French Defense Minister Florence Pali said on the 24th, France will add hundreds of millions of euros in the space defense budget, the development of space military forces, to prevent other countries may carry out“unfriendly moves ” in outer space.
The French budget for military space projects will increase from 3.6 billion euros (约合 4.2 billion) to 4.3 billion euros (5 5 billion) between 2019 and 2025, Pali told Provence newspaper the same day.
In accordance with the French Military Planning Act 2019-2025, approved by the French Parliament in 2018, France is expected to update its existing observation and communication satellites, launch three electromagnetic listening satellites and modernize space surveillance radars.
French President Emmanuel Macron announced last July that a space military command and an“air and space Force”would be established within the French Air Force.
Paley said she will officially announce the formation of the space force when she visits a military academy in Salon, Provence, later.
The space force, which is part of the Air Force, will be 500 by 2025, Mr. Paley said.
“Gone are the days when people thought that space services served the common good of science, " she said.Today, space is a place for nations to compete for global hegemony.”
Pali reiterated Macron's previous statement, saying France has no intention of provoking an arms race.
"We are by no means engaged in an arms race.But it is my responsibility to fully recognize the threats that we may face.”
Pali recalled the surveillance of a military satellite shared by France and Italy in 2017.
She said it was a Russian satellite that was“ peeping on."
The Russian side denies this claim.
France will“soon”have small patrol satellites capable of spotting and targeting“those behind unfriendly moves,”Mr. Paley said.
French media believe that France sought the establishment of a space force, because US President Donald Trump last February asked the United States Department of Defense to draft the establishment of a space army bill.
Trump signed the Defense Authorization Act last December, approving the creation of the United States ' sixth-largest army, the Space Army.
Some experts worry that the US moves have accelerated the pace of US space militarization and could trigger a new space arms race.
