They rarely make mistakes.
They are able to repair themselves and maintain a long life.
There is a super interesting thing about natural systems.
If we can translate it into our built environment, there's a lot of potential in the way we build things.
I think the key is self-assembly.
If we want to use self-assembly in our own physical environment, I think there are four key factors.
The first is that we need to decode all the complexity of what we want to build-that is, our buildings and machines.
We need to decode them into simple sequences -- basically the DNA of how our buildings work.
Then we need the programmable part that can accept the sequence and use it for folding or remodeling.
We need some energy to activate, so that these parts of us can fold up in accordance with the procedure.
We need some type of error correction redundancy to ensure that what we successfully build is what we want.
