These projects are large-scale reconfigurable robots-8-foot, 12-foot long proteins.
They are embedded in electromechanical devices, sensors.
You need to decode the way you want to fold into, into, a series of angles -- negative 120 degrees, negative 120 degrees, 0 degrees, 0 degrees, 120 degrees, negative 120 degrees-- that sort of thing; a series of angles, or turns, that can be passed through with a wire.
Each cell gets its own message -- say, negative 120. It rotates, checks to see if it rotates in place and passes the sequence to its neighbors.
There are many outstanding scientists, engineers,designers working for this project.
I think this project really reveals: is this really scalable?
I mean, it costs thousands of dollars a lot of people to build this eight-foot robot.
Can we really expand it?Can we really embed robots in every part?
The next question is to look at the passivity, or passively try to make the reorganization programmable.
But it goes a step further, and it tries to do the actual calculations.
Basically embedded in the basic building blocks of most calculations, digital logic gates, directly into the various parts.
This is with the non-door.
There is a tetrahedron on each gate to be used for the calculation, with two input tetrahedron.
One of them is input from the user, just like you're building bricks.
The other is the input of a brick that comes before the front is placed.
Then it will give the output of three-dimensional space.
This means that users pile up bricks the way they want.
It is calculated based on what you have done and your instructions.
Now it begins to move in three-dimensional space-up or down.
Looking to the left, the input of[1,1] is equal to the output of 0, which means down.
On the right, the input of [0,0] is an output of 1, indicating up.
So what this really means is that our structure now contains the blueprints we want to build.
So the information about what you want to build is all embedded in it.
This means that we have some form of self-replication.
In this case, I call it self-directed replication, because your structure contains precise blueprints.
If you encounter an error, you can replace a section.
