Israel strengthens prevention and control of repeated outbreaks
In the early days of the outbreak of new crown pneumonia, Israel's prevention and control measures have been effective.
However, with the gradual lifting of the ban on prevention and control measures, the number of confirmed cases of new crown pneumonia in Israel has risen significantly in recent years. The Israeli government has taken several urgent measures to strengthen the prevention and control of the epidemic.
On February 28, the first case of new crown pneumonia was confirmed in Israel. It quickly closed all ports of entry and exit, suspended non-essential industries, changed schools to online classes, restricted public transport and non-essential social activities, blocked cities with severe outbreaks, and jointly maintained preventive and control measures by the military and police.
The series of measures quickly paid off, and by mid-May, new confirmed cases of new crown pneumonia in Israel had dropped to single digits in one single day.
Since June, the number of new confirmed cases of new crown pneumonia has gradually rebounded as the epidemic has been brought under control and all Israeli prevention and control measures have been lifted.
Especially after entering July, the spread of the epidemic has been accelerating.
In recent days, Israel has more than 1,500 new cases per day for eight days, and as of press time on July 25, 916 new cases have been added on that day.
As of 25 July, there were 59,745 confirmed cases and 448 deaths in Israel.
In the face of the rapid rebound of the epidemic, the Israeli government has repeatedly taken urgent measures to strengthen the prevention and control of the epidemic.
On July 6, after the number of confirmed cases exceeded 30,000, the Israeli government closed gyms, swimming pools, bars, nightclubs and other public entertainment venues, and introduced a policy of restricting public transport, requiring a maximum of 20 passengers per bus.
On the 17th, the government announced a series of new restrictions, including the implementation of“city closures”on weekends, including the implementation of“city closures”between 17: 00 on Fridays and 5: 00 on Sundays.
During this time, people can go out, but shops, shopping centers, barbershops, beauty salons, libraries, zoos, museums, exhibition halls, swimming pools and tourist attractions will be closed, while basic services such as supermarkets and pharmacies will remain open.
At the same time, on all dates and time periods, gatherings of more than 10 people are prohibited, gyms, studios and other places will be closed, restaurants and cafes are prohibited from dine-in, only take-out services are allowed.
At the same time, the Israeli public has not paid enough attention to the severity of the outbreak and has not been able to work with the government to combat it.
After repeated outbreaks in Israel, many people took to the streets to protest against the government's control measures affecting their economic interests.
On July 11, tens of thousands of people staged a demonstration in Tel Aviv, arguing that anti-epidemic policies were affecting the economy.
On the evening of the 21st, thousands of protesters gathered in front of the official residence of Prime Minister Netanyahu in Jerusalem to protest against Prime Minister Netanyahu's promulgation of a ban on restaurants, cafes and other preventive measures without compensation.
In addition, many people do not comply with the requirements of wearing masks and maintaining a safe social distance of two meters when they are outdoors. In order to avoid being fined by the police for not wearing masks, many people only wear masks on their chin or hang them on their wrists.
During the repeated epidemic, schools are the hardest hit areas of the spread of the new crown virus, and according to reporters recently visited this kindergarten found that the kindergarten teachers and students did not wear masks as required by the government, did not maintain a safe social distance of two meters from each other, for a large number of teachers and students infected with the virus buried hidden dangers.
Professor Eli Waxman, a member of the Expert Advisory Group on combating the epidemic of the Israeli National Security Council, believes that Israel is moving towards a“dangerous situation”, noting that the current measures taken by Israel to prevent and control the epidemic are not enough and that all leisure and recreational activities and summer schools should be closed to control the further spread of the epidemic.
Waxman said Israel lacked an overall plan to combat the outbreak. Parliament and government departments should abandon their interests as soon as possible and agree on clear steps to combat the outbreak, including restrictions in different sectors.
