Many people think that driving is something that only those who can see can do.
Blind people want to drive a car alone safely until now, is also considered an impossible task.
Hello everyone, my name is Dennis Hong, and for the freedom and independence of the blind, we have built a car designed for people with visual impairment problems.
Before I talk about this blind car, let me briefly describe another project I've worked on called the U.S. Department of Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency Urban Challenge.
It's about making a mechanical car that can drive on its own.
You press the start button, no longer touch anything, it can reach its destination completely automatically.
At the 2007 challenge, our team won 美元 500,000 to take third place in the competition.
Around that time, the National Society for the Blind, or the Society for the Blind, challenged the design team about who could design a car that would allow the blind to drive independently and safely.
We thought we'd try it, because we thought, hey, where's this going to be?
We already have an automatic car.
All we have to do is let the blind drive inside, and that's it, right?
(Laughter) But we were wrong and unreliable.
What the Blind Association wants is not a car that can carry the blind around, but a car that the blind can take the initiative to make a choice and drive.
So we had to give up everything we had and start from scratch.
To test this crazy idea, we designed a prototype of a small sand truck to test its feasibility.
In the summer of 2009, we invited a lot of blind youth across the country and gave them a chance to use the car for a ride.
It's definitely a cool experience.
But the problem with the car is that it is designed to allow blind people to drive in very limited circumstances, like a closed parking lot-even on a path made of red traffic cones.
So with this success, we decided to take the important next step, to build a real car that can travel on a real road.
So how does it work?
Well, it's a relatively complex system, but let me explain it and simplify it.
We have three stages.
We have the induction phase,the computational phase and the non-visual interface.
The driver is obviously invisible, so the system must be able to sense the surrounding environment and collect data for the driver.
In this regard, we use the initial metering element.
It measures acceleration, angular acceleration -- like the human ear, the inner ear.
I combined this information with the global positioning system to predict the location of the vehicle.
We also use two cameras to detect the path of the car.
We also use three laser rangefinder.
The laser scans the environment to detect obstacles -- vehicles passing from the front and back, as well as any obstacles that break into the road, and any obstacles around the vehicle.
All the massive information is then aggregated into the computer, the computer will do two things.
First of all, one thing is to process information to understand the surroundings-which are driving paths and which are obstacles-and to translate that information to the driver.
This system is also very intelligent to calculate the safest driving path.
We can also issue instructions on how to operate the operating procedures of the vehicle.
But the question is: How can we transmit information and instructions quickly and accurately to a blind person to ensure that he can drive?
To this end, we have designed many different non-visual user interface technologies.
The original three-dimensional flat sound system, vibration vests, voice-activated gears, leg straps, and even shoes that put pressure on the feet.
But today we are talking about three of these non-visual user interface technologies.
The first interface is called the driver's handle.
This is a pair of gloves, in the knuckles it has a vibration element, so that you can transmit instructions on how to travel-direction and amplitude.
Another device is called a velocity shock band.
This car chair -- actually, it's a massage chair.
We take it out, we reorganize the vibration elements of different modes. We let them to transmit speed information, but also have instructions on how to use the throttle and brake.
Here you can see how the computer understands its surroundings. Because you can't see the vibration, we actually put a red light-emitting diode on the driver so he can see what's going on.
This is the sensor data, which is transmitted from the sensor to the computer.
So these two devices, the driving handle and the speed shock belt, are very effective.
But the problem is that these are instruction-suggestive devices.
So it's not really freedom, is it?
The computer tells you how to drive -- turn left, turn right, accelerate,brake.
I call this the co-pilot problem.
So we are avoiding the command hint device, and focus more on the information device.
A typical example of such a non-visual information interface is called an empty graph.
Think of this as a display for the blind.
This is a small table top, with a lot of holes on it, compressed air is removed from it, so that it can be described as a picture.
So even if you're blind and you put your hand on it, you can sense the course of action and the obstacles.
In fact, you can also change the frequency of release in the air, and possibly the temperature.
This is actually a multidimensional user interface.
Here, you can see the cameras on the left and right sides and how the COMPUTER parses and transmits this information to the empty map.
In this way, we are showing a simulation program in which a blind man is driving with an empty map.
This app is of great help in training blind drivers and quickly testing different theories based on different kinds of non-visual user interfaces.
That's basically how it works.
But the car is a model car, and it won't hit the road unless it's proven to be as safe to drive as today's cars, or safer to say so.
I really believe this will happen.
But will society, and will they, accept this radical idea?
How will we deal with insurance?
How will we issue a driver's license?
There are many different obstacles behind the technical challenge that we need to address before it really becomes a reality.
Of course, the main purpose of this project is to design a blind-driven car.
But what is potentially more important than that is the enormous value in the byproducts of the project.
A sensor that can be used to see dark, rain and fog.
And with this new kind of interface, we can use these technologies to make them safer for visual people.
Or for the blind, the daily life of the household devices-educational facilities, office facilities application services.
Imagine that in class the teacher writes notes on the blackboard blind students can also use these non-visual interfaces to understand and read what the teacher has written.
This is extremely precious.
Today, what I'm showing you is just the beginning.
Thank you very much.
(Applause）
